Posted: Tue Apr 09, 2013 8:57 pm
dj2k4 wrote:Lone Shepherd,Are you on Time Warner Cable? Have you tried the following guide to blocking ISP peering for youtube?It might be worth a try.Be aware that although this does seem to work for some people, the solution involves permanently blocking inbound connections from more than 67,000 publicly routable IP addresses (one /16 plus one /24). This could easily break stuff that has nothing to do with YouTube and if so, when you come across that broken thing in, say, six months time, are you going to remember that you blocked all those addresses? Probably not. More likely, you won't be able to fix the problem and will end up blaming the service.In other words, this is rather like dropping a nuke on a city in order to swat a fly.
